            <section aria-labelledby="theory-heading" class="prose">
              <h2 id="theory-heading">How this pipe sizing calculator works</h2>
              <p>
                This tool sizes circular water pipes using the Darcy–Weisbach
                equation with an iterative friction factor (Swamee–Jain
                approximation). It supports two common design approaches:
              </p>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Limit velocity</strong> to control noise, erosion and
                  water hammer.
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Limit pressure drop</strong> to maintain adequate
                  downstream pressure.
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Key equations</h3>
              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Continuity (flow vs. diameter):</strong></p>
                <p>$$ Q = V \cdot A = V \cdot \frac{\pi D^2}{4} $$</p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\(Q\) = volumetric flow rate</li>
                  <li>\(V\) = average velocity</li>
                  <li>\(D\) = internal diameter</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Darcy–Weisbach pressure loss:</strong></p>
                <p>
                  $$ \Delta P = f \cdot \frac{L}{D} \cdot \frac{\rho V^2}{2} $$
                </p>
                <p>where:</p>
                <ul>
                  <li>\( \Delta P \) = pressure drop</li>
                  <li>\( f \) = Darcy friction factor</li>
                  <li>\( L \) = pipe length</li>
                  <li>\( \rho \) = fluid density (water ≈ 1000 kg/m³)</li>
                </ul>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p><strong>Reynolds number:</strong></p>
                <p>$$ \mathrm{Re} = \frac{\rho V D}{\mu} $$</p>
                <p>
                  where \( \mu \) is dynamic viscosity (depends on temperature).
                </p>
              </div>

              <div class="formula-box">
                <p>
                  <strong>Swamee–Jain friction factor (turbulent flow):</strong>
                </p>
                <p>
                  $$ f = 0.25 \left[ \log_{10}\left( \frac{\varepsilon}{3.7D} +
                  \frac{5.74}{\mathrm{Re}^{0.9}} \right) \right]^{-2} $$
                </p>
                <p>where \( \varepsilon \) is absolute roughness.</p>
              </div>

              <h3>Typical design velocities for water</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  <strong>Domestic cold water:</strong> 3–8 ft/s (1–2.5 m/s)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Chilled water / HVAC:</strong> 4–10 ft/s (1.2–3 m/s)
                </li>
                <li>
                  <strong>Suction lines:</strong> often kept lower (e.g., &lt; 5
                  ft/s or 1.5 m/s)
                </li>
              </ul>

              <h3>Limitations</h3>
              <ul>
                <li>
                  Assumes clean water at moderate temperature and full pipe
                  flow.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Minor losses from fittings/valves are not explicitly included;
                  you can approximate them by increasing the effective length.
                </li>
                <li>
                  Results are for straight circular pipes; always check against
                  local codes and manufacturer data.
                </li>
              </ul>
            </section>

            <section aria-labelledby="faq-heading" class="prose mt-8">
              <h2 id="faq-heading">FAQ</h2>

              <h3>What is a good design velocity for water pipes?</h3>
              <p>
                For most building water systems, 3–8 ft/s (1–2.5 m/s) is a
                common range. Lower velocities reduce noise and water hammer but
                require larger pipes. Higher velocities increase pressure drop
                and risk of erosion.
              </p>

              <h3>Should I size by velocity or by pressure drop?</h3>
              <p>
                Both matter. Velocity limits protect the pipe and system, while
                pressure drop limits ensure enough pressure at fixtures or
                equipment. In long runs, pressure drop usually governs; in short
                branches, velocity limits are often used.
              </p>

              <h3>Does this calculator include fittings and valves?</h3>
              <p>
                No, it models only straight pipe friction. A practical approach
                is to add an equivalent length for fittings (e.g., 20–50% extra
                length) or to check the final pressure margin and adjust as
                needed.
              </p>

              <h3>What pipe schedules are suggested?</h3>
              <p>
                The tool compares the required internal diameter to common
                nominal sizes in Schedule 40 and 80. For high-pressure or
                industrial systems, always verify wall thickness and allowable
                pressure with the manufacturer or applicable standards.
              </p>
            </section>
